Paratroope: aMissile Command clone. J-Bird: a Q-Bert rip of the highest order (I also vastly prefer it!). I have no idea how they got away with PC-MAN, which is essentially a Pac-Man port. Orion games were as important to me as the "real" ones. I had so much pride in Auburn for having this studio.

Putin is likely afraid of having over 700,000 Russian veterans return to Russia in the event of demobilization out of fear that veteran groups could threaten the stability of his regime upon their return. 

Putin launched a deliberate campaign to suppress veteran civil societies.üßµ
The Kremlin seeks to silence voices capable of meaningfully objecting to the continuation of Russia‚Äôs aggression in Ukraine or questioning Russian government decisions.

Putin is likely trying to avoid a modern analog to the veterans-based civil society born from the Soviet withdrawal from Afghanistan. The Kremlin likely fears political instability such as what followed the Soviet withdrawal from Afghanistan in 1988-1989.

It is falsely framing its efforts to co-opt veteran life as preventative measures against the reemergence of ‚ÄúAfghan syndrome‚Äù - a Russian term used to describe the aftermath of the Soviet government‚Äôs failure to reintegrate traumatized veterans into society upon their return from Afghanistan.

The Kremlin is likely particularly concerned that veterans‚Äô return could trigger a new wave of "Afghan syndrome" and the rise of new veterans groups critical of the Russian war effort or military - especially because the Kremlin failed to militarize and mobilize Russian society for a protracted war.

The Kremlin faced the threat of an emerging veteran opposition movement against the Putin regime between late 2022 and mid-2023 when patrons - such as Wagner financier Yevgeny Prigozhin - tried to weaponize Russian servicemen and veterans to advance personal political objectives.

The Kremlin launched several initiatives starting late 2022 to co-opt loyalist veteran figures and form state-controlled veterans organizations in support of the permanent militarization of Russian society at the federal, regional, and local levels.

These initiatives include:
-designating 2025 as the Year of the Defender of the Fatherland
-Defenders of the Fatherland State Fund
-Time of Heroes" Higher School of Public Administration 
-Association of ‚ÄùSpecial Military Operation‚Äù Veterans & "SVOi" Military Brotherhood
-censorship & centralization

The Kremlin first launched various immediate force centralization, censorship, and repression efforts in late 2022 through mid-2023 to eliminate the immediate threat of an emerging anti-Putin veteran civil society.

These efforts aimed at arresting voices that resonated with or weaponized the veteran communities such as Prigozhin, Russian ultranationalist Igor Girkin & former 58th Combined Arms Army (CAA) Major General Ivan Popov.
Putin officially declared 2025 the ‚ÄúYear of the Defender of the Fatherland,‚Äù signaling the Kremlin‚Äôs growing commitment to expanding state control over veterans‚Äô lives and civil society.
The Kremlin launched the Defenders of the Fatherland State Fund in April 2023 as a long-term initiative intended to coopt veterans by monopolizing all veterans' support initiatives and funds.

The Kremlin is likely establishing the fund as the sole mechanism through which veterans can receive compensation, possibly making it harder for independent veterans civil society to seek funding outside the government framework.

The Kremlin established the "Time of Heroes" Higher School of Public Administration in February 2024 to form a new Russian elite composed of a limited number of loyal and ultranationalist veterans that will continue to militarize the Russian society over the long term.

The Kremlin appears to be using the "Time of Heroes" program to elevate ardent ultranationalists and loyalists to positions of power on the local, regional, and federal levels under the guise of empowering veterans.

novayagazeta.eu/articles/202...
The Kremlin uses the "Time of Heroes" program to set conditions for permanent recruitment and militarization of Russian society to continue its aggression against Ukraine and possibly against NATO.

The Kremlin created the Association of ‚ÄúSVO‚Äù Veterans in November 2023 & the ‚ÄúSVOi‚Äù Military Brotherhood in October 2024 to replace other existing veteran civil societies that have been critical of Russia‚Äôs conduct of the war in Ukraine but essential for supporting Russian training & recruitment.

The establishment and rapid development of the Association of ‚ÄúSVO‚Äù Veterans and the ‚ÄúSVOi‚Äù Military Brotherhood demonstrate that the Kremlin is prioritizing establishing administrative, financial, and organizational control over Russian veterans‚Äô communities and organizations in 2025.

The United States and Ukraine‚Äôs allies must consider the Kremlin‚Äôs fear of emerging veteran civil society groups and demobilization when assessing Russia‚Äôs negotiating position and the requirements for enduring peace in Ukraine and Europe.

The Kremlin's focus on co-opting and establishing a state-controlled veterans civil society indicates that the Kremlin assesses that societal effects from Russia‚Äôs war in Ukraine can pose significant risks to Putin‚Äôs regime‚Äôs stability.

The Kremlin has seemingly been successful in alleviating the immediate threat of the alienated veterans' civil society in mid-2023 and has been relatively successful in ensuring that the Putin regime does not face a similar political threat in the short term.

The Kremlin may also be expanding this campaign to recreate in part the temporary Soviet success in reintegrating veterans following World War II to condition Russian veterans and society for a greater confrontation with NATO in the future.
A near-constant state of military mobilization is therefore one of the least politically risky configurations for Putin.
This dynamic will likely prompt Putin to maintain high levels of military readiness to simultaneously set conditions that would allow him to sustain a protracted or future war against Ukraine...
and/or prepare for a confrontation with NATO while minimizing the threat that Russian veterans may undermine his regime.

Eggesford Hunt 03.03.25

At the beginning of March a small team of us visited one of Eggesford Hunt‚Äôs favourite areas around Riddlecombe and Ashreigney.  The hunt were meeting at Paul John (aka Lord Farquaad) and Katie Craddock‚Äôs home on the edge of the village. üßµü¶ä 01/27

Katie is Torrington Farmers huntsman Steve Craddock‚Äôs daughter and Paul John needs no introduction, if you‚Äôre a regular follower of our page! For those who do need a reminder: www.facebook.com/devoncountyh... 02/27
Paul‚Äôs performance on the day within minutes of the hunt setting off from the meet might just have topped the above, so watch this space for Lord Farquaad episode 2, coming soon! 03/27
midst the predictable homophobic and misogynistic remarks and threats to ride us down with his horse or launch us over a hedge, 04/27
we were also subjected to some more entertaining verbal diarrhoea, being called ‚Äúhugging tree cunts‚Äù and told to ‚Äúgo eat our fucking carrot cake and rice biscuits‚Äù. 05/27
All jokes aside, Paul‚Äôs horse was clearly not happy about being yanked at the reins and ridden at us repeatedly. But then what do you expect from a disgraced ex-jockey! 06/27
After running out of steam and realising he‚Äôd struggle to get off his horse without Katie‚Äôs help, Paul eventually left us to it and we didn‚Äôt see much of him for the rest of the day. 07/27

The first draw of the day was between Colehouse and Coldharbour, where a fox was seen running across a field away from hounds. Hounds doubled-back to the east and marked a different fox to ground at a badger sett near Colehouse. 08/27

This was the first of many marked badger setts that day, all of which we kept an eye on, including remotely.

From Colehouse the hunt moved south into the valley towards Higher Narracott. 09/27
Sabs were perfectly positioned to witness a fox go to ground at another sett in the valley, shortly before hounds arrived on that fox‚Äôs line. 10/27
Sabs sprayed to cover the scent line and rated hounds when they arrived, sending them back onto the heel line and causing Jason to gather them and move them on to the west. 11/27
Our drone spotted another fox running from hounds at the next draw, but fortunately the fox had a decent head start and the warm sunny weather caused hounds to scatter and lose the scent. 12/27
Via Lake and Ley the hunt then headed north in direction of Ashreigney to draw land belonging to South Farm. We know this particular piece of land extremely well. 13/27
While foot sabs were repositioning, we hovered our drone directly over a large badger sett straddling the field/wood boundary and witnessed hounds mark another fox to ground there. 14/27

Jason moved the hounds on from there but we knew this was one terrierman Richard Elliott would be keen to dig-out if given the chance. Sure enough, about half an hour later we spotted him sneaking back to that sett. 15/27

While a foot sab made a beeline to the sett to disrupt any attempted digout, our vehicle drove to a viewpoint and started filming from the road. Elliott spotted the vehicle and rather pathetically tried to hide his quadbike behind a hedge. 16/27

When he turned around and realised he was now being filmed from all directions, he picked up his mate and drove off.

Having moved Elliott and his gimp on from the sett, we went to catch up with Jason, who by now had cast hounds into the woods north of Churchwater Bridge. 17/27

Hounds ended up scattered over a large distance, running off in many different directions on various bits of scent. When we caught up with Jason on the road, he had just one hound with him. Many had gone north towards Heale Farm, 18/27
into the woods on both sides of the road where the hunt are banned from entering. Our vehicle followed Jason up the road to Heale Farm as he tried to call hounds back to the road. 19/27
Eventually he got off his horse and ran into the valley to the north to gather them up on foot. A foot sab followed him in and discovered hounds marking yet another sett in the valley. 20/27
Knowing the hunt was banned from this land, Richard Elliot meanwhile managed to convince the landowner it was OUR fault the hounds were scattered all over her land. 21/27

Quite how he did this, considering the only horn and voice-calls ringing across the valley for the past hour had been Jason‚Äôs, is unclear! Unclear also why the landowner would believe a hunt terrierman, whose very presence is evidence of illegal activity. 22/27
Everything moved on to the west and hounds were cast into the valley between Bolts and Furze Barton. Two foxes were seen running, their getaway assisted by sabs. 23/27
Richard Elliot tried to scare one of the foxes back from a badger sett, to prevent the fox from going to ground and force a chase, but this fox got away. 24/27
At this point Jason gave up and hacked back to the meet, while his minions drove around picking up hounds who were scattered all over the Ashreigney and Riddlecombe area. 25/27

It was nice to encounter lots of enraged anti-hunt landowners in the area. It was nice also to see many healthy-looking foxes escape the hunt, including one who crossed the road in front of us at the end after the hunt had packed up. 26/27

The season is nearly over, but you can still support our work via www.paypal.me/dchs. If you see a hunt while you're out and about, send us the location via text to, email, or message any of our social media accounts. 27/27

"...the Trump administration has already made its plans quite clear. If it means that AI develops faster, and that America beats China, it can be part of the plan. If it gets in the way of that, it‚Äôs off the table."
